04452nam a22007455i 9783110962321DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20131996gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)999371805  a97831109623217 a10.1515/97831109623212doi  a(DE-B1597)46435  a(OCoLC)853269309  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPB2273.A7 Z72 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a491.6/6a491.66a891.66111 aIsaac, Graham R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Verb in the Book of Aneirin :bStudies in Syntax, Morphology and Etymology /cGraham R. Isaac.  aReprint 2011 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2013] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (483 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBuchreihe der Zeitschrift für celtische Philologie ,x0931-4261 ;v120 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe "Book of Aneirin" is a thirteenth-century manuscript collection of Welsh praise-poetry. In comparison with other Welsh sources of similar date, the language of this text exhibits a number of features which have been interpreted as archaisms and taken as indications of great antiquity for the text. However, particularly in syntax, claims about the status of these 'archaisms' have not been discussed in the context of the grammatical organisation of the text as a whole. This book approaches various aspects of grammar against the background of a comprehensive edition of the finite verbal clauses of the text. Syntactic analysis of the data-base so established takes its point of departure from the relationship of the verb with its arguments in the clause, and is concentrated on two issues: 1. the type and status of basic word order in the text; 2. the interaction of the semantics of the predication with the pragmatics of communication of information. It is argued that, as would be expected for a Welsh text, the basic order is VSO, but also, and more importantly, that the text does not contain 'archaic' evidence of any earlier, different basic orders. Rather it is argued that word-order variation in the text can be rigorously analysed in terms of a model of functional syntax which is sensitive to both the pragmatics of the text and the semantics of the predications involved. In the light of these results, argumentation concerning historical syntax and especially reconstruction of syntax are evaluated, both in the field of Celtic and in wider cross-language perspective. Finally, the edition of the finite clauses of the text is followed by a number of notes discussing historical and synchronic aspects of the material presented, with particular emphasis on morphology and etymology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aWelsh languageyTo 1100xEtymology. 0aWelsh languageyTo 1100xMorphology. 0aWelsh languageyTo 1100xSyntax. 0aWelsh languageyTo 1100xVerb. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Literary and Cultural Studies - 1990 - 1999z9783110637830oZDB-23-GLC0 cprintz978348442912340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311096232140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110962321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110962321/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-GLCc1990d1999